In this lesson you will move through a number of information screens which will teach you about Privacy.
You will also be presented with scenario pages, where a situation will be described involving a number of fictitious characters. You will be asked questions which will test your understanding of Privacy.

These questions are not scored and your response is not recorded. Use the feedback provided to consolidate what you have learned during this lesson.

Description.div: This module should take about 5 minutes.
You will be given a brief introduction to the Privacy Act.
Privacy training will help you do your job and may also help you as an everyday consumer.
At the end of this module you should have a clear understanding of:

ul.li: what the Privacy Act is about
why it is important to your organisation
the role of the Privacy Commissioner
what happens if your organisation breaches the Privacy Act

Description.div: When you are ready click on the next button below to start training.

Page.Title: What does the Privacy Act do?

Description.div: The Privacy Act sets out rules for handling "personal information", that is, information or opinions about individuals.
This training program only covers the NPPs. It is therefore intended for use by organisations which have chosen not to establish or be bound by a privacy code at this time.

div.strong: Is the Privacy Act Effective Now?

Description.div: The Privacy Act has been part of Australian law since 1988. Major changes which affect you and your organisation were made to the Privacy Act in 2000. These changes started on 21 December 2001.

Page.Title: Who does the Privacy Act apply to? Who must comply?

Description.div: The Privacy Act places obligations on organisations.

Anything done by you as an employee in the course of your work is treated as if it were done by your employer. So it is important to your organisation that you know your privacy obligations and comply with them.
In this program, references to 'you' and 'your' mean both your organisation and you as an individual employee at work.
You should not do anything with personal information acquired at work except what your organisation has authorised you to do.

Page.Title: What information does the Privacy Act cover?

Description.div: The NPPs apply to "personal information" held or collected by an "organisation" for inclusion in a "record".
"Personal information" is information or an opinion about an individual whose identity is apparent or can reasonably be ascertained from that information or opinion.

An "organisation" means an individual, body corporate, partnership, any unincorporated association or trust with an annual turnover of more than $3 million. An "organisation" also includes any body corporate that has a related body corporate with an annual turnover of more than $3 million.
A "record" is a document, record in a database (however kept), photograph or other pictorial representation of a person.
The Federal Privacy Commissioner is appointed under the Privacy Act to enforce the Act and to provide advice and guidance about privacy issues to organisations and the general public.
There is a wide range of information available from the Office of the Privacy Commissioner.

div.strong: What happens if your organisation breaches the Privacy Act?

Description.div: If an individual thinks your organisation has breached the NPPs they can complain to the Commissioner. Remember, anything done by you as an employee in the course of your work is treated as if it was done by your employer. So your breach of the NPPs is a breach by your employer.

The Commissioner can investigate the complaint and make a determination. The Commissioner can order your organisation to apologise, publish a correction, or do a range of other things including pay compensation to people who suffer loss because of its breach. The Commissioner can seek to enforce these orders in the Federal Court.
The Commissioner is also likely to publicly "name-and-shame" any organisation found guilty of a breach. This could result in adverse publicity for your organisation.
